What is a Form?

A form collects user input.

Example:

<form>
    <input type="text">
    <button>Submit</button>
</form>
Basic Form
index.html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Forms</title>
</head>
<body>

<form id="loginForm">

    <label>Name</label><br>
    <input type="text" id="name"><br><br>

    <label>Password</label><br>
    <input type="password" id="password"><br><br>

    <button type="submit">
        Login
    </button>

</form>

<script src="script.js"></script>

</body>
</html>
Reading Input Values ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
script.js
let form = document.getElementById("loginForm");

form.addEventListener("submit", function(event){

    event.preventDefault();

    let name = document.getElementById("name").value;
    let password = document.getElementById("password").value;

    console.log(name);
    console.log(password);

});

If user enters

Name : Priya

Password : 12345

Console

Priya
12345
What is .value?

For HTML elements:

<input id="username">

Use

let username =
document.getElementById("username").value;

.value returns what the user typed.

preventDefault() ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Normally,

After clicking Submit,

the page refreshes.

To stop refreshing,

event.preventDefault();

Without it

Click Submit

↓

Page Reload

With it

Click Submit

↓

No Reload
Form Validation ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Validation means checking whether the entered data is correct.

Example

Name should not be empty
Password should have at least 6 characters
Email should contain "@"
Example 1
form.addEventListener("submit", function(event){

    event.preventDefault();

    let name =
    document.getElementById("name").value;

    if(name===""){

        alert("Name cannot be empty");

    }

});
Example 2

Password Length

let password =
document.getElementById("password").value;

if(password.length<6){

    alert("Password must be at least 6 characters");

}
Multiple Validation
form.addEventListener("submit", function(event){

event.preventDefault();

let name=document.getElementById("name").value;

let password=document.getElementById("password").value;

if(name===""){

alert("Enter Name");

return;

}

if(password.length<6){

alert("Password too short");

return;

}

alert("Login Successful");

});
Trim Input ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Suppose user types

"     "

It is not empty.

Use

if(name.trim()===""){

alert("Enter Name");

}

trim() removes spaces from the beginning and end.

Email Validation

HTML

<input
type="email"
id="email">

JavaScript

let email =
document.getElementById("email").value;

if(!email.includes("@")){

alert("Invalid Email");

}
Reset Form
form.reset();

Example

alert("Success");

form.reset();

All input fields become empty.

Common Mistakes
❌ Forgetting .value

Wrong

let name=document.getElementById("name");

console.log(name);

Output

<input ...>

Correct

let name=document.getElementById("name").value;

Output

Priya
❌ Forgetting preventDefault()

Without

event.preventDefault();

the page refreshes before you can process the data.

❌ Using ==

Prefer

if(name==="")

instead of

if(name=="")

because === checks both value and type.

Interview Questions ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
1. What is form validation?

Form validation ensures the user enters valid and complete data before it is submitted.

2. Why use preventDefault()?

It prevents the browser's default action, such as reloading the page after form submission.

3. How do you read input values?
let value = document.getElementById("inputId").value;
4. Why use trim()?

trim() removes extra spaces from the beginning and end of a string.

Example:

"  Priya  ".trim();

Result:

"Priya"
